spanGrp.span: Je (_) je je (_) jẽk pajiö-gẽ je yokö-gẽ
Once can see that he is well-dressed.
kepa í jẽk sũã'-gẽ-nẽ Jẽk sũã'-gẽ-nẽ-nã sũã'-glö jie (_) (_) jẽk pajiá-wã rö böi nẽ
There he eats and leaves the house.
Jeska í í yukö-gẽ í dugesãũ jũ shebega
A car was coming, which gives him a lift and takes him along.
Taranã jeska este karro dajũ e-gla estee ra Karro dajũ (_) je të jie jiegẽga tse-gẽ-mĩ-ite jeska í tse-gẽ-mĩ-ite-ra nã
It rushes through a mountain and gets to where it was heading.
í jũr-gẽ kögẽũ kabata nã kabata nã kepa je-wa (_) í dö-ge-mĩ-ũka mãĩ dö-ge-mĩ
In the middle of the road something appears, a small frog.
ñala mõshã' bi í ra nã Jirö (_) desãũ ñala ska Jirö (m) desãũ sapo yuli desãũ
It thought the driver would stop the car,
jie í begetsá-nã jie të je jie jie të karro (_) estee wökkewẽ-wã-pa-nẽ
but it went on and crashed against a stone.
Jeska í káu ñawösiga mẽnẽũ buganã' jak mẽ
the small mouse ended up in a branch;
koño yuli je pakkácha/ jẽk jẽk bötsága kaljula nã
the other hit his head and feet on a stone.
ta e-gla je mẽnẽũ tsagu buganã' jak mẽ klö buganã' jak mẽ
The small frog saw that it was his fault that the others got hurt.
Je shkanã' je sapo yulei të í sũã'-ra-nã jie jie batawa nẽ je siga-wa ñã shká-wã
So he went away and hid under a stone;
je kueinga mẽnẽũ-lo-mĩ-nẽ je mẽnẽũ-mĩ í (m) jẽk pakká-wã jak diginã
then he saw that the other was hurt;
so he hurried to see him and saw that he was hurt indeed.
Shka-nã' je kueinga jie jie mẽnẽũ bekti í sũã' të sũã' chöglë í shka-nã'
He cried that it was his fault.
Kueinga í mẽnẽũ-te ele i jiñã' köũnã jie batawa í rö nẽ
At that point the mouse came down and saw that the other one did not heal;
Jeska e-gla jawãte koño jẽk jawãte nẽranã je të sũã'-ra e-gla ka böi-nã
the other cried out for help so he could get cured.
Jebi bö kueinganã e-gla je (_) wã/ e-gla të í e-gla (_) chagá-nẽ-nã pe bötö-nẽ í sũã-nẽ ta je të pe bötö-nẽ í sũã' je të je wã sũã'-glö-nã (_) je wã í tsõ-glö-mĩ-nẽ je wã í böi-nẽ-wã-glö
He took him in the car;
Mẽnẽtse-mĩ í wã estee ĩã/ ka (_) karro ĩã kueinganã
they took him and the frog stayed crying that it would be his fault if the other one died.
Jeska mẽnẽtse-mĩ jatanã jiñõ-nẽ-nã (_) je döá-wã-ra-nã je rö jie jie batawa nẽ
He went, came back and saw that the other one was coming all wrapped up,
Í mẽnẽũ-mĩ kepanã í deu-nẽ-ra-nã sũã'-ite-ra-nã sũã'-ite-ra-nã estee tögapanã í í je e-gla dajũ-nẽ je e-gla dajũ-wã paböt-lë-wã kable dajũ-nẽ rö estee
The other one brought him a bed;
Kueinganã e-gla du-gẽ ĩã estee du-gẽ ĩã jaka du-gẽ ĩã
the other one then brought him a blanket,
Tögapa e-gla du-gẽ-wã í ra jẽk kĩtiö-glö du-gẽ ĩã
Tögapa e-gla dugẽũ je të í chewẽ-gẽ
and gave him food in his mouth.
je të jirö mẽ-gẽ ĩã kö nã
The other one took off his bandage, the blanket;
Tögapanã e-gla të klabe jirö pamõ-lë í mẽ (_) í í yaka mẽ je kable yetule-gẽ-mĩ kable í kobija yetule-gẽ-mĩ
then he thus lied for quite some time in bed.
Je kueinganã jewanã jie të tögapa jeska í senã' jaka inga tã'ĩ
Later on, when he healed, he could walk again;
Tögapa je (_) í í (_) í í böi-nã'-nẽ-ra-nã e-gla e-gla ya dé-ka-nẽ böi Shká-ka-nẽ-ra-nã
the other one told him that he almost died because of him.
e-gla të í shá ĩã jie batawa kasi döá-wã rö
So this other one jumped joyfully because that other one had healed.
Je kueinganã jie jie tunã' jie tunã' köũ jie ksenã-ka-nã e-gla böi-nã-nẽ
Then they hit the road; a car passed by, picked them up and took them.
Tögapa í tsõ-nẽ etaba_gicha í beteu-lo (_) ñala wa etaba_gicharanã y y ka (eh) karro damãũ e-gla të jie-wa jiá-ka
They all went together because the other one had not died
mẽnẽtse-mĩ í wã kable ñara Je kueinganã í í kable mẽnẽũ-lo-mĩ-nẽ ñara porke ñẽ e-gla böi-nã-nẽ ka e-gla dönẽ-wã
but had got cured and could survive.
